Predicting wine quality

The goal of this notebook is to train and evaluate different models on the Wine Quality Dataset.

Report

Models

We analyze the performance of four models with different structures, namely:

  • Logistic regression,
  • Random forest,
  • XGBoost,
  • TabPFN

Data

The Wine Quality Dataset (source) served as the training and evaluation foundation for all the models discussed. Before running the code , ensure that you've downloaded the dataset and placed the CSV file in the same directory as this notebook.

Input variables (based on physicochemical tests):

  • fixed acidity
  • volatile acidity,
  • citric acid
  • residual sugar
  • chlorides
  • free sulfur dioxide
  • total sulfur dioxide
  • density
  • pH
  • sulphates
  • alcohol

Output variable (based on sensory data):

  • quality flag (-1 or 1)

Results

Comparison of models in terms of ROC-AUC score:

  • Logistic Regression: This basic model provided a foundational benchmark for performance, but was surpassed by more complex models.
  • Random Forest: Demonstrated superior performance, standing out as the top contender among all the models evaluated.
  • XGBoost: While it outperformed logistic regression, it couldn't quite match the performance of Random Forest.
  • TabPFN: This model notably outshines both logistic regression and XGBoost. However, it falls marginally short of the results from Random Forest.

It's also worth noting that the use of SMOTE consistently led to a decline in ROC-AUC performance across all models.

In[147]:
def calculate_metrics(y_true, y_pred_prob, threshold=0.5):
    y_pred_labels = [1 if prob > threshold else 0 for prob in y_pred_prob]
    
    auc = roc_auc_score(y_true, y_pred_prob)
    precision = precision_score(y_true, y_pred_labels)
    recall = recall_score(y_true, y_pred_labels)
    f1 = f1_score(y_true, y_pred_labels)
    
    results = {
        'ROC AUC Score': auc,
        'Precision': precision,
        'Recall': recall,
        'F1 Score': f1
    }

    show_plots(y_test, y_pred_labels, y_pred_prob)

    return results


def show_plots(y_true, y_pred, y_pred_prob):
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)
    cm_df = pd.DataFrame(cm, index=['Actual Negative', 'Actual Positive'], columns=['Predicted Negative', 'Predicted Positive'])


    fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(15, 6))
    
    # Confusion Matrix
    sns.heatmap(cm_df, annot=True, cmap='Blues', fmt='g', ax=ax1)
    ax1.set_title('Confusion Matrix')
    ax1.set_ylabel('Actual Values')
    ax1.set_xlabel('Predicted Values')
    
    # ROC Curve
    fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(y_test, y_pred_prob)
    ax2.plot(fpr, tpr, color='blue', label='ROC curve')
    ax2.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], 'r--')
    ax2.set_xlim([0.0, 1.0])
    ax2.set_ylim([0.0, 1.05])
    ax2.set_xlabel('False Positive Rate')
    ax2.set_ylabel('True Positive Rate')
    ax2.set_title('Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) Curve')
    ax2.legend(loc="lower right")
    plt.show()
In[148]:
def train_eval_model(model, X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test):
    kwargs = {'overwrite_warning': True} if isinstance(model, TabPFNClassifier) else {}
    model.fit(X_train, y_train, **kwargs)
    y_pred_prob = model.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1]
    results = calculate_metrics(y_test, y_pred_prob, threshold=0.5)
    return results, y_pred_prob

model_probs = {}

def print_model_eval(model_name, model, model_probs=model_probs, X_train=X_train, y_train=y_train, X_test=X_test, y_test=y_test, X_train_sm=X_train_sm, y_train_sm=y_train_sm):
    print(f"{model_name}:")
    metrics, y_pred_prob = train_eval_model(model, X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test)
    model_probs[model_name] = y_pred_prob
    for metric_name, metric_value in metrics.items():
        print(f"{metric_name}: {metric_value:.4f}")

    if X_train_sm is not None and y_train_sm is not None:
        model_name += ' with SMOTE'
        print(f"\n\n{model_name}:")
        metrics_sm, y_pred_prob = train_eval_model(model, X_train_sm, y_train_sm, X_test, y_test)
        # model_probs[model_name] = y_pred_prob
        for metric_name, metric_value in metrics_sm.items():
            print(f"{metric_name}: {metric_value:.4f}")
